@NODE Introduction "sort v1.80 Documentation - Introduction"
  I  had  to sort some very large files.  First I tried the Workbench sort
command  ...   and  cancelled the command after a long time.  The computer
seemed to have hang up, nothing happened.
  Then I tried to get a sort program from Aminet ...  I couldn't find one,
that was fast enough and able to meet my requirements on making changes to
the file.

  So  I  had  to  decide to forget about sorting these files or to write a
program,  which has all required functions and the speed first of all.  As
you can see, I decided to go this way.

  The  basic function of the sort program is sorting files in alphabetical
order.   But its functions are not limited to sorting.  I have implemented
many options which allow to manipulate file(s) in different ways.

A detailed description of all options is available @{" here " link Features}.
The sort program is to be started from the Shell.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "sort v1.80 Documentation - Requirements"

Nothing  else is needed than a computer (preferable Amiga :-) with a shell
and files to sort, too.
For large files a respective amount of memory is needed.

This program is available for different computer @{" platforms " link Availability}.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE History "sort v1.80 Documentation - History"
Version 1.00 - 1.20
internal versions
written on a PC because of lack of a working C-Compiler for AMIGA

Version 1.21
adapted to AMIGA

Version 1.22
removed the bug that the program crashes if a line in input file is longer
than the limit.  But 1024 Byte is quite long.  So I don't think it will be
reached.  If yes after all, the bytes which are too much will be cutted.

Version 1.23
added the -n|N switch
Translated the program into English, optimized the code.

Version 1.24
made some changes on the part where switches are interpreted
now some contradictions removed

Version 1.25
the loading routine completely new implemented, now needs less memory

Version 1.30
implemented an improved algorithm for sorting.
Now the speed is more than twice as fast as before.

Version 1.31
optimized the erasing of blank lines, so sorting becomes faster
added some colors

Version 1.32
optimized setting of switches
added  -j|J  switch;  now  it's  possible  to join as much files as memory
allows  removed  some bugs, which could be troublesome (actually every bug
is this)

Version 1.33
added -f[y] and -l[y] switch
now it's possible to sort within a given range, of course the speed
becomes a little slower due to additional code in the sorting routine.
if no range is given the speed is around 10 per cent faster as before

Version 1.34
removed a bug which could be fatal.
Due to some changes in the sorting routine the speed has been increased
again.

Version 1.35
don't remember, because of the long time which has gone (holidays...)
oh yes, added the -s option

Version 1.36
added the -P option
the -s option can now be used also in a given range, means it works now as
the other functions too.
as usual the sorting speed could be increased a little bit again

Version 1.37
added the -c option
now its possible to sort files after a given number of column.
due to that the need of memory to manage the list is slightly bigger
then removed a minor bug, that while joining files exactly on file less
is loaded as given.  Now it's ok.  of course it was found only after
uploading the previous version :-(

Version 1.38
removed a minor bug, which actually doesn't bother, but who knows ...
added a check if the output file already exists.

Version 1.38a
Bugfix.
The -o option didn't work anymore due to check for the file existing.
Now it works.

Version 1.41
modified the load routine, added "pointer buffering" to the sort algorithm.
depending on file, sort time reduced to 50% - 25% compared to Version 1.38
used mempools routines © by Jochen Wiedmann for allocating and freeing the
memory, time for memory management reduced downto 2 (two) percent

Version 1.42
changed -c option
Now the file is sorted after the column given by the first number, for
sorting the number of chars are used given by the second number.
added -v option
If this switch is given, no message appears, except of error messages.
added -S option
Now a single char (the first given) can be replaced by another one
(the second given)

Version 1.43
Bugfix
the join option didn't work properly
the messages of the program looked funny
added -C option
same as -c, but the -E / -N option uses the column for comparison, after
which is sorted.

Version 1.44
added -i option
added a new algorithm to prepare the list for sorting
now the sorting speed is 6 (six) times faster than before

Version 1.45
recoded the load routine (for Amiga Version only)
Needs much less time to load the files and in fact no (recognizable)
time to free the memory
Memory usage reduced by about 30%
mempools package is not needed any longer

Version 1.46
removed a bug which could occur, if binary characters are in the file
no maximun length of a line for AMIGA version anymore

Version 1.47
removed a bug in line calculation

Version 1.48
added the -q|Q option. it divides a file according to the given search
pattern.

Version 1.49
some smaller improvements

Version 1.50
added -t option. it deletes spaces and tabs at the end of lines in the
file/range.
added -h option. Header lines can be ignored now.
added -I option. same as -i, but sorted is in two passes. with this option
all double lines will be erased if the -E is set.
changed -i option. now different strings can be ignored
changed -E|N option.  -t option is now set automatically with these
switches made the sorting routine faster
increased the sorting speed

Version 1.60
added -b|B Option. now the sort program has also a numeric sort facility.
changed -I Option. now the -E option is set automatically, if this option
is chosen

Version 1.61
found and removed a little bug.
increased the write speed for the second file (-q|Q)

Version 1.62
Bugfix

Version 1.70
added -w   option. shows the lines which are erased
added -z   option. allows more than one line per set of data
routine for evaluating the switches rewritten.

Version 1.80
added -A   option. appends outfile to a file, if it already exists
added -u   option. erases all lines which are completely in another line
added -y|Y option. sorting column starts after a search pattern at a variable
                   position. this option works together with -i|I option.
added -Z   option. allows to sort binary (!) files. Requirement is a constant
                   length of data record.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE


@NODE Installation "sort v1.80 Documentation - Installation"

  This is quite easy:

Just copy the sort program into the C: directory or whereever you want.
For this you can use the Install Script, if the Commodore Installer is
on your system.

It is advisable to include this directory into the path, so you have the
sort program always ready for use.

If you have enough memory, you could made the program resident, so it's
faster to start.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

