   @{" -a   " link A} @{" -A   " link Ä} @{" -b|B " link B} @{" -c|C " link C} @{" -d   " link D} @{" -e|E " link E} @{" -f   " link F} @{" -g   " link G} @{" -h   " link H} @{" -i|I " link I}
   @{" -j|J " link J} @{" -l   " link L} @{" -n|N " link N} @{" -o   " link O} @{" -p|P " link P} @{" -q|Q " link Q} @{" -r   " link R} @{" -s|S " link S} @{" -t   " link T} @{" -u   " link U}
   @{" -v   " link V} @{" -w|W " link W} @{" -x   " link X} @{" -y|Y " link Y} @{" -z|Z " link Z}

-x	disables the sorting function

@{" Contents " link MAIN} @{" << " link W} @{" Features " link Features} @{" >> " link Y}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Y "sort v1.80 Documentation - Features - y|Y"

   @{" -a   " link A} @{" -A   " link Ä} @{" -b|B " link B} @{" -c|C " link C} @{" -d   " link D} @{" -e|E " link E} @{" -f   " link F} @{" -g   " link G} @{" -h   " link H} @{" -i|I " link I}
   @{" -j|J " link J} @{" -l   " link L} @{" -n|N " link N} @{" -o   " link O} @{" -p|P " link P} @{" -q|Q " link Q} @{" -r   " link R} @{" -s|S " link S} @{" -t   " link T} @{" -u   " link U}
   @{" -v   " link V} @{" -w|W " link W} @{" -x   " link X} @{" -y|Y " link Y} @{" -z|Z " link Z}

-y	this option sets the sorting column after a special search pattern.
	this option works together with -i option. First the sorting column
	is set after the search pattern the -i option is carried out.

-Y	the sorting column is set after a search pattern. At first the file
	is sorted without this option, then double and empty lines are
	deleted. In the second run the file is sorted after the sorting
	column is set.
	This option works together with -I option.  Firstly the -I option
	is carried out, then the -Y option

@{" Contents " link MAIN} @{" << " link X} @{" Features " link Features} @{" >> " link Z}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Z "sort v1.80 Documentation - Features - z"

   @{" -a   " link A} @{" -A   " link Ä} @{" -b|B " link B} @{" -c|C " link C} @{" -d   " link D} @{" -e|E " link E} @{" -f   " link F} @{" -g   " link G} @{" -h   " link H} @{" -i|I " link I}
   @{" -j|J " link J} @{" -l   " link L} @{" -n|N " link N} @{" -o   " link O} @{" -p|P " link P} @{" -q|Q " link Q} @{" -r   " link R} @{" -s|S " link S} @{" -t   " link T} @{" -u   " link U}
   @{" -v   " link V} @{" -w|W " link W} @{" -x   " link X} @{" -y|Y " link Y} @{" -z|Z " link Z}

-z[x]	<x> contains the number of lines per set of data so it is also
	possible to sort files in which more than one line belongs to
	a set of information.
	The number of lines in the file should be a multiple of <x>,
	remaining lines at the end of the file are cut off.

-Z[l,c]	<l> sets the number of characters per set of data, <c> the number
	of characters that are used for sorting.
	sets of data may contain binary characters outside the sorting area.
	Size of file should be a multiple number of sets of data, remaining
	characters are cut off.

@{" Contents " link MAIN} @{" << " link Y} @{" Features " link Features}  >|
@ENDNODE

@NODE Examples "sort v1.80 Documentation - Examples for use"
sort textfile1
asks for the outfilename and loads 'textfile1'. After sorting it will be
written to <outfile>. Suggestion for the outfilename is 'textfile1.sort'


sort textfile1 RAM:text.out -g
loads 'textfile1', sorts without distinguishing capitals and small letters
and writes the sorted file to 'RAM:text.out'


sort dir1/textfile1 dir2/textfile2 -j3 textfile3 RAM:text.out -E
loads 'textfile1' 'textfile2' and 'textfile3' from different paths, sorts,
removes all blank lines and all identical lines (except of one of them)
and writes the list to 'RAM:text.out'


sort RECENT RECENT.sort -E -c20,10 -g -f6
is the common command line to sort the 'RECENT' files from Aminet
sorting starts at line 6, means the header is not touched.
it is sorted by the types of the files, additionally the entries are
sorted by the first column.
blank lines and identical lines are deleted (the whole line is used for
comparision)


sort RECENT ram:file1 -g -E -c20,10 -pdev/ -q/e
sorts the Aminet 'RECENT' file by the type of program, erases all lines
which don't contain "dev/" and divides the remaining file into one, which
lines contain the string "/e" (written to 'RAM:file1') and one, which lines
doesn't contain the string '/e' (written to 'RAM:file1.ohne')


sort RECENT1 RECENT2 RECENT3 RECENT4 -j4 ram:file1 -g -E -c20,10 -h0,5 -f6
joins four files (in this example four different 'RECENT' files from
Aminet), removes in files 'RECENT2', 'RECENT3' and 'RECENT4' the first
5 lines (the header) and starts sorting at line 6 of the joined file by
column 20 for 10 characters (this is the place where the type of files is).
Capitals and small letters are not distinguished and all double lines are
erased after sorting.
The resulting file is saved to RAM:file1.


sort file1 -j3 file2 file3 ram:big_file -px -qy -E -g
loads 'file1', 'file2' and 'file3', picks out all lines which contain the
string "x" (means delete all lines which doesn't contain it), sorts the
file without distinguishing capitals and small letters, deletes all double
lines.  After that all lines which don't contain the string "y" will be
written to 'RAM:big_file.ohne', the rest to 'RAM:big_file'.


sort woebu1 woebu2 -j2 -E -g -I<ignore_list woebu.gesamt
joins the files 'woebu1' and 'woebu2', sorts them first without ignoring
any strings, removes the blank and identical lines and sorts again, this
time ignoring all strings which are in the file 'ignore_list'.
Capitals and small letters are not distinguished

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Tips "sort v1.80 Documentation - Tips and Hints"
The switches can be set at any place after the program name.
If the parameter to the switch is not given, it will be asked for.
The program detects contradictions between given switches to avoid possible
mistakes from the user

Notice that the outfilename has to be the last of all filenames.
If no outfilename is given, the first infilename plus a new ending is used
for a suggestion for the outfilename.

The sort-order bases on the strcmp/stricmp function.

if characters like " are given it is advisable to give this switch as the
very last of the command line.  The reason is that the following arguments
are not recognized after a " by the programm.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs "sort v1.80 Documentation - Known Bugs"

None so far.

In case you find any bugs, please report them with the exactly
specification of the call, the used options.
If possible, send also the file where the bug occured in to this
@{" address " link Author}.  Thank you.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Registration "sort v1.80 Documentation - Registration"

After registering you will get a registration number, which enables all
features in the sort program.
The latest versions are on the Aminet and on my @{" Amiga Page " link Author}

In case you'd like to use this program on an other system, see
for which computer @{" platforms " link Availability} this program is available too.

For registration send the fee of 10 DM or alternatively 6 US$ or Ł 4.
to this @{" address " link Author}.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Availability "sort v1.80 Documentation - Availability"
this program is available for the following systems:

  - AMIGA     - Ultrix 4.4     - SUN OS 4.1.3    - Linux
  - MS-DOS    - Solaris 2.4    - AIX 3.2.5

  The package is available via aminet (util/sys) or from my homepage:
http://www.iee.et.tu-dresden.de/~wernerr/amiga.html

  The latest version will be available from my page, for all above
mentioned systems.

  In case you want to use the program on a system which is not mentioned
here send me an e-mail and tell me, what system you are working on.

@{" Contents " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE
